          "body": "Before the full weight of judgment falls, God inserts a mercy-shaped intervention that the text almost buries: 'I will hedge up her way with thorns and build a wall against her so that she cannot find her paths' (2:6). This is not cruelty — it is the divine pastoral strategy of removing access to the idols before they destroy her entirely. The result, in 2:7, is a prodigal-son moment avant la lettre: 'Then she will say, I will go back to my first husband, for it was better for me then than now.' The obstruction works. She does not repent from virtue; she repents from frustration — the lovers cannot be caught, cannot be found. But God is content to use even the failure of idols to turn her face homeward. Jonathan Edwards observed that God often employs secondary causes, even the failure of sinful pursuits, as instruments of conviction. Hosea 2:6-7 is that principle in narrative form. The thorns that tear her dress are a mercy more profound than clear roads to destruction."
